'''AOL Seed''' was an [[open content]] submission website and platform operated by [[AOL]] from 2009 to 2012, when it was closed. Writers and photographers were able to submit their work, and then get paid for each work submitted. The work was then circulated throughout [[AOL]]'s network of websites . It was run by [[Saul Hansell]], a former technology reporter for ''[[The New York Times]]''.<ref>http://www.clickz.com/clickz/news/1688663/aol-hires-first-seedcom-employee-nyt-journo-saul-hansell</ref>
AOL Seed has been compared to [[Associated Content]], a website with a similar model, now owned by [[Yahoo]].<ref>{{cite web |accessdate=2010-06-07 |url=http://www.businessinsider.com/aol-seedcom-2009-12 |title=AOL's Seed.com Pays Well, But Feels Like "A Black Hole" |publisher=Business Insider }}</ref> The platform was part of AOL's strategy of positioning itself as an online news and information company.<ref>{{cite news |accessdate=2010-06-07 |url=http://news.smh.com.au/breaking-news-world/aol-plants-seed-for-internet-age-news-operation-20100317-qf97.html |title= AOL plants Seed for Internet Age news operation |work=Sydney Morning Herald |date=2010-03-17}}</ref> After AOL acquired the [[Huffington Post]] in 2011, Seed was no longer core to this strategy.
