'''Jordan Canning''' is a director for film and television. She is known for her independent feature films ''[[We Were Wolves]]'' (2014) and ''Suck It Up'' (2017), as well as her work directing on television series ''[[Baroness von Sketch Show|Baroness Von Sketch Show]],'' [[Burden of Truth (TV series)|''Burden of Truth'']] and ''[[Schitt's Creek]]''.
==Early life== She was born in [[St. John's, Newfoundland and Labrador|St. John's]], [[St. John's, Newfoundland and Labrador|Newfoundland]].
==Career== Canning's films have won a number of awards, including two [[Golden Sheaf Awards]],<ref>[http://www.goldensheafawards.com/default.aspx?page=208&a=w&y=2012 "2012 Golden Sheaf Award Winners"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130411031727/http://www.goldensheafawards.com/default.aspx?page=208&a=w&y=2012 |date=2013-04-11 }}. ''[[Yorkton Film Festival]]''</ref><ref>[http://www.goldensheafawards.com/default.aspx?page=208&a=w&y=2010 "2010 Golden Sheaf Award Winners"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130411032918/http://www.goldensheafawards.com/default.aspx?page=208&a=w&y=2010 |date=2013-04-11 }}. ''[[Yorkton Film Festival]]''</ref> three awards at the [[National Screen Institute|NSI Online Short Film Festival]],<ref>[http://www.nsi-canada.ca/2012/09/jordan-cannings-not-over-easy-wins-all-three-nsi-online-short-film-fest-awards/ "Jordan Canning’s Not Over Easy wins all three NSI Online Short Film Fest awards"]. ''[[National Screen Institute]], September 13, 2012''</ref> and top prize at the 2012 [[2012 Toronto International Film Festival|Toronto International Film Festival]] RBC Emerging Filmmaker Competition.<ref>[http://tiff.net/industry/programmes/emergingfilmmakers "RBC Emerging Filmmakers Competition Winners 2012"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130404191806/http://tiff.net/industry/programmes/emergingfilmmakers |date=2013-04-04 }}.</ref><ref>[http://www.thetelegram.com/Arts%20-%20Life/Entertainment/2012-09-06/article-3068839/Salty-and-sweet-pays-off-for-Jordan-Canning/1 "‘Salty and sweet’ pays off for Jordan Canning"] ''The Telegram'', Tara Bradbury September 06, 2012.</ref> She directed all twenty-three episodes of the IPF-supported web series ''Space Riders: Division Earth'' for [[CTV Main Channel|CTV]]. The show won the 2014 [[Canadian Screen Awards|Canadian Screen Award]] for Best Digital Series and four [[Canadian Comedy Awards]], including Best Director.
Canning's 2014 feature film ''[[We Were Wolves]]'' screened at the Toronto Film Festival and is distributed by Unobstructed View.<ref name="playback">[http://playbackonline.ca/2014/10/01/jordan-cannings-we-were-wolves-gets-distribution/ "Jordan Canning’s We Were Wolves gets distribution"]. ''Playback Online'', October 1, 2014 by Etan Vlessing</ref>
In 2015, Canning was awarded the Women In the Director's Chair Feature Film Award<ref name="WIDC">[http://www.widc.ca/jordan-canning-wins-120000-prize-widc-feature-film-award-announced/ "Jordan Canning Wins $120,000 Prize: WIDC Feature Film Award Announced"]. WIDC, March 2, 2015 by Carol Whiteman</ref> for her second feature film, ''Suck It Up'' (2017), which premiered at the 2017 [[Slamdance Film Festival]] and is distributed by Level Film. The film won Best Feature Film at the 2017 B3 Frankfurt Biennale.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.b3biennale.de/id/7975/B3-BEN-AWARD-2017-Congratulations-to-the-winner/|title=B3 BEN AWARD 2017: Congratulations to the winner! - B3 we talk about - B3 Biennale|last=Biennale|first=B3|access-date=2017-12-28}}</ref>
In 2016, Canning made her foray into television, directing on ''[[Saving Hope]]'' and ''[[This Hour Has 22 Minutes]]'', where she became the first female director on the show. The following year she directed nine episodes of television on the series ''[[The Detail]]'' ([[CTV Television Network|CTV]]), ''[[Burden of Truth (TV series)|Burden of Truth]]'' ([[CBC Television|CBC]]/[[The CW]]), and [[Baroness von Sketch Show|''Baroness Von Sketch Show'']] ([[CBC Television|CBC]]/[[IFC (U.S. TV channel)|IFC]]).<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/newfoundland-labrador/jordan-canning-22-minutes-director-1.3877281|title=Newfoundland filmmaker becomes first female 22 Minutes director|last=|first=|date=|work=|newspaper=CBC News|access-date=2016-12-20|via=}}</ref> In 2018 she directed seven episodes of ''[[Schitt's Creek]]'' Season 5, two episodes of [[Little Dog (TV series)|''Little Dog'']] ([[CBC Television|CBC]]) and half the season of [[Baroness von Sketch Show|''Baroness Von Sketch Show'']] season four.
Canning is a 2010 graduate of the Director’s Lab at the [[Canadian Film Centre]] and an alumnus of TIFF Pitch This! and Talent Lab.
